         <div type="commentary">
            <!--commentary encoded as per section §9.3 
            Notes
st. I: Is there any way that Advaya can be a synonym of Kāma = Anaṅga? See the next stanza and my note on it. My reading against Krom is supported by Kuburajo I, l. 2-3 Ādvayavarmmamputra.
	vaṁśa ... amarārya: this seems to be an expression corresponding to the Amarāryakula found in the “Mallar (Bilasapur, M.P.) copper-plates of Vyāghrarāja of the reign of Pravararāja.” (See file Lielukhine Orissa+Andhra received from Manu.) It must mean ‘lineage of the best among the immortals’ and hence be synonymous with the Indravaṁśa of other Ādityavarman inscriptions.
	śilālekha: the word is attested in Gudam I, and also in the Chaiya inscription (śelālekha).
	Note on king’s virtues: cf. Minye Tujuh kāruṇṇya kāsiḥ taduḥ.

st. II kāmarāja: cf. Anaṅgavarman ‘King Cupid’ in Saruaso II. 
	adhimukti is a Buddhist technical term; so is abhijña. Ṣaḍabhijña: epithet of the Buddha! Cf. Amarakośa/Candrakiraṇa.
	I take nāmnābhiṣeka ... dheya as meaning ...abhiṣekanāmadheyena.
	I take adhirājarāja in the sense of rājādhirāja (inverted compound).

l. 7  dharmmarājakulatilaka: allusion to the Dharmarājan of the Chaiya inscription?

l. 8-9 maṅuddharaṇa ... yaṁ tallaḥ jīrṇṇa: this is an explication of the common expression jīrṇoddhāra, alluded to in Ombilin, st. II, Rambahan, st. V, and Batu Bapahat I, st. III, and very likely in st. III below.

l. 9 sapta svarṇṇabhūmi: cf. Gudam II, st. III. Is this an expression for a concrete sevenfold division of the realm? Or only an allusion to the idealistic ‘seven constituents’ alluded to in l. 8? See Rāmeśvarapura inscription of Kṛtanagara, and ciri of the Sulalat al-Salutin.

l. 10 pañcamahāśabda: this is a title much used in Indian epigraphy. It seems most commonly to denote the right to carry five honorary titles. (Add references to Schmiedchen; Sircar.) The use of nan seems to be a Minangism. Contrast inan in demonstrative function further below. However, the i- of demonstratives is separable (cf. modern dialectal ni, tu and nan), so the difference nan/inan may not be significant, and nan may here be postposed with kalampura.

l. 14 tuluta: should be a verb with irrealis suffix ‘may be BLESSED he who ...’ 

Final prose paragraph: this type of colophon is found also in Buddhist texts in India, e.g. in the Abhiṣekanirukti: abhiṣekaniruktiḥ samāptā || kṛtir iyaṁ paṇḍitasujayaśrīguptapādānām || ||          
            
